title: Pricing of catastrophe reinsurance and derivatives using the Cox process with shot noise intensity
abstract:
We use the Cox process (or a doubly stochastic Poisson process) to\ud
model the claim arrival process for catastrophic events. The shot noise process\ud
is used for the claim intensity function within the Cox process. The Cox process\ud
with shot noise intensity is examined by piecewise deterministic Markov process\ud
theory. We apply the model to price stop-loss catastrophe reinsurance contract and\ud
catastrophe insurance derivatives. The asymptotic distribution of the claim intensity\ud
is used to derive pricing formulae for stop-loss reinsurance contract for catastrophic\ud
events and catastrophe insurance derivatives. We assume that there is an absence\ud
of arbitrage opportunities in the market to obtain the gross premium for stop-loss\ud
reinsurance contract and arbitrage-free prices for insurance derivatives. This can\ud
be achieved by using an equivalent martingale probability measure in the pricing\ud
models. The Esscher transform is used for this purpose
